question: Both of these passages end off on a cliffhanger, leaving readers to predict what might happen next. Pick one of the story excerpts and write an original ending of your own. Write the next two paragraphs of one of the stories, describing whats you imagine would happen next. Try to match the writing style of the author.
rationale: The passage questions require students to do a great deal of inferring. This entire assignment would be a great assignment for students who have difficulty predicting, inferring, or extending themselves beyond what is directly written.

question: Some of the story excerpts that you just read communicate a mood of urgency and danger. Write an essay in which you identify the passages that have an urgent mood and analyze the techniques the authors used to develop the mood.
rationale: Identifying mood is a topic that students likely have practiced in or before sixth grade, but students will experience more rigorous challengs as they will be required to identify authors' techniques themselves (which could be character development [like dialogue or characters' actions] or figurative language [which was commonly used in \The Great Glowing Forest\" and is the topic of many of the MC questions for this topic]). "

question: Which of the passages address the big idea of responding to enemies? In two paragraphs, identify which passages best address the main idea. Provide textual evidence to prove your point, and analyze how these passages relate to the idea of reacting to enemies.
rationale: Both \Shortest War Ever\" and \"King Tut's Sandals\" touch on the topic of enemies. This similar idea can serve as a commonality as students compare and contrast the texts. Given that it is such a broad idea
updatedAt: students will have to work independently to find textual evidence that can be used to further elaborate on the similarity.  "

question: The two passages in this assignment are from the same story, but they are told from differing points of view. From what perspective is the first passage told? Who is the narrator of the second passage? Explain who appears to be narrating each passage, and why changing narrators may be useful in a story.
rationale: Very few point-of-view questions according to a recent audit done by Geoffrey.

question: Time period is an important part of the setting of a story. Write a paragraph in which you determine if each of the following passages is set in the past, present, or future. Use textual evidence and any background information you know to help you explain the settings you chose for each passage.
rationale: While students in early elementary school have a background in identify the setting's physical location, placing a passage within a time period (ie., past or present, or even a specific historical era) can be more challenging. This assignment requires students to look for clues to the time period and apply (or develop) their background knowledge to determine time periods for text.

question: All three of the passages are examples of fantasy stories. Write a response in which you explain what aspects of each story causes it to be classified as fantasy. Be sure to include textual evidence.
rationale: While students in grade 5 likely can identify the genre of a passage, this open-ended question requires students to provide evidence as to why a passage best falls within a specific genre. This will require students to make note of stylistic plot elements, the usage of certain settings, and character archetypes in order to draw similarities between common writing structures and genre.
